QLHV monitor, both completed successfully, while a third subagent under the Lead direct session is still running. I'm also seeing another session with the label \"DTLX Full API Test v2\" that I need to examine more closely. Looking at the session state from 06:34 UTC, the three cron sessions were active and the Telegram session had completed. Comparing that to now at 06:40, I see the Telegram direct session is back to running, which is interesting since it was marked done at 06:34—though the updatedAt timestamp of 1776235171596 suggests it may have resumed work after completing.\n\nThe `cron:e7885813` session also shows a new message since then, even though it appeared in the earlier state. Both of these are normal session continuations, not actual changes from the baseline. I'm noticing something odd though—there's a subagent running from the Lead direct session called \"DTLX Full API Test v2\" that might be significant.\n\nBut wait, that subagent actually failed earlier with an error about reading undefined properties, and its updated timestamp is older than the last state check. Same with the other subagents under that Lead session—they're all in failed or completed states from earlier cycles, so nothing's actually new there.\n\nLooking at the bigger picture, I have three cron sessions all still running, the Lead Telegram session continuing its work, and the ecosystem group chat idle as expected. The orphaned cron instances are still lingering from before. The pipeline seems stable overall, but I'm trying to figure out if the Telegram session being back online counts as a meaningful change since it was briefly completed before resuming.\n\nThe real question is whether I should send a report now. The Telegram session did complete at 06:34 but then resumed work by 06:39, which could look like a session resurrection to the Lead. The core question is whether the three cron sessions are genuinely new or just the same instances continuing to run from the earlier report. Looking at the heartbeat data, the timestamps show they're still active, but I need to verify if they've actually cycled or if this is just a monitoring artifact from when the state file was captured. So the status change from \"done\" back to \"running\" is definitely a new event—the session resumed work after completing its task. Since the heartbeat-state was captured when the session was marked done, and now it's active again with the orchestrator continuing its README edits, this qualifies as a change worth reporting to the lead. Looking at the heartbeat timestamps, the cron sessions and Telegram activity are all stable with no failures, so the pipeline looks healthy overall. But I should flag the Lead's Telegram session reactivation in the report since that's a state change worth noting.\n\nNow I'm realizing there's a timing issue with the state file—it was last written at 06:34 UTC, but I should verify whether the session states I'm comparing against are actually current or if they've been updated since then. The `cron:e7885813` session with the aborted message appears in the 06:34 UTC state and remains running, so that's consistent. For `telegram:direct:6053576134`, I need to check what the last recorded state was since it's not in the heartbeat file at all—that might indicate it was a newer session or already marked as done by then.\n\nLooking at the system message history, it shows the Lead direct session completed around 05:35 UTC, which aligns with the session being \"done\" by 05:36 UTC. So the session ended normally after delivering the Agent Status report.\n\nNow at 06:39 UTC, the same session is back to \"running\" status with an updated timestamp of 06:39 UTC. This could mean either the session resumed work after completing its task, or it's just the session's heartbeat updating even though it finished its work. Looking at the message history, it's actively making edits to the README, so it seems to be continuing operations.\n\nSince the session transitioned from done back to running between the 06:34 and 06:39 snapshots, this represents a state change I should flag. Let me compile the report with this update, the stable pipeline status, and the active session count. I've verified the MCP and cron statuses are all functioning properly, and the pipeline is healthy with no failures. The only significant change since the last report is that the Lead's Telegram session resumed activity—it's now editing the README again after being marked complete at 06:34. I should send a brief notification about this state transition to keep the team informed.","thinkingSignature":"14de014c219c1b0c2269b362b99c722fc9a1d8e33846d97f86565a7b1a8d2418"},{"type":"text","text":"Comparing current state (06:40 UTC) vs. heartbeat-state.json (06:34 UTC):\n\n**Last known:** `cron:ed2d0b5d` ✅ `cron:e7885813` ✅ `cron:6f3323ef` ✅ — `telegram:direct:6053576134` = **done** (completed normally)\n**Current:** `cron:ed2d0b5d` ✅ `cron:e7885813` ✅ `cron:6f3323ef` ✅ — `telegram:direct:6053576134` = **running** (resumed editing README)\n\nChange detected: Lead direct session reactivated. Sending report to group -5163901258.\n\n---\n\n🟡 Orbis — 5p Update | 06:40 UTC 15 Apr\n\nChanges detected:\n• 🔄 `telegram:direct:6053576134` (Lead session) — resumed from \"done\" back to active (continuing README edits)\n\nPipeline: HEALTHY ✅\n• Active sessions: 4 (QLHV 5p ✅ DTLX 5p ✅ Agent Status ✅ Lead direct ✅)\n• MCP: stitch ✅ confluence ✅ gitlab ✅\n• Cron: 5p progress ✅ | Daily @ 5AM+7 ✅\n• Blockers: cron:ac986a8d orphan (~45h) | cron:b653a6c0 orphan (~40h) — low priority\n\n— Orbis 🌐"}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"ahvholding","model":"AHV-Holding-DEV","usage":{"input":20644,"output":1711,"cacheRead":13944,"cacheWrite":436,"totalTokens":36735,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1776235274344,"responseId":"062e660b882dca40e7132d1f578bf14b"}}
